class Solution {

    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) {

        int row = 0;
        int col = matrix[0].length - 1;

        while (row < matrix.length && col >= 0) {

            if (matrix[row][col] == target) {
                return true;
            }
            else if (matrix[row][col] > target) {
                col--;
            }
            else {
                row++;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}


Problem Description

You are given an m × n integer matrix where:

Each row is sorted in ascending order from left to right.
Each column is sorted in ascending order from top to bottom.

You are also given an integer target.

Your task is to determine whether the target exists in the matrix.

Return true if the target is found.
Return false if the target is not found.
Example 1
Input
matrix =
[
 [1, 4, 7, 11, 15],
 [2, 5, 8, 12, 19],
 [3, 6, 9, 16, 22],
 [10,13,14,17,24],
 [18,21,23,26,30]
]

target = 5
Output
true
Explanation

The number 5 is present in the matrix at:

Row = 2
Column = 2

(Using 1-based indexing.)

So the answer is true.

Example 2
Input
matrix =
[
 [1, 4, 7, 11, 15],
 [2, 5, 8, 12, 19],
 [3, 6, 9, 16, 22],
 [10,13,14,17,24],
 [18,21,23,26,30]
]

target = 20
Output
false
Explanation

The number 20 does not exist anywhere in the matrix.

So the answer is false.

Constraints
m == matrix.length
n == matrix[i].length

1 ≤ m, n ≤ 300
-10^9 ≤ matrix[i][j] ≤ 10^9
All rows are sorted in ascending order.
All columns are sorted in ascending order.
-10^9 ≤ target ≤ 10^9
Approach
Start searching from the top-right corner of the matrix.
If the current element is equal to the target, return true.
If the current element is greater than the target, move left.
If the current element is smaller than the target, move down.
Continue until the target is found or you move outside the matrix.
Time Complexity
O(m + n)
Space Complexity
O(1)
